	"content": "<h1 class=\"page-title\">Week 11</h1>\n  \n  <div id=\"todo-date-mount-point\"></div>\n  \n    <div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"section\" style=\"background-color: rgb(100.000000%, 100.000000%, 100.000000%);\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Overview</span></strong></p>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"section\" style=\"background-color: rgb(100.000000%, 100.000000%, 100.000000%);\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Diversifiable or unsystematic risk, unidversifable or systematic risk, achieving diversification through portfolios, index models, calculating the alpha and beta of an asset, Treynor-Black Model</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Learning Objectives</span></strong></p>\n<p>Upon completion of this week, you will be able to understand:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>how diversification helps reduce risk in a portfolio</li>\n<li>decompose the risk of an asset into systematic and idiosyncratic components</li>\n<li>link between systematic risk and exposure to macroeconomic variables</li>\n<li>the market as the source of systematic risk in single index models</li>\n<li>calculate the alpha and the beta of an asset</li>\n<li>use single index models to simplify the portfolio allocation problem</li>\n<li>with single index models the optimal risky portfolio becomes a combination of an active portfolio and a passive portfolio (the Treynor-Black model)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Preparation for class</span></strong></p>\n<p>Mandatory reading: <span class=\"instructure_file_holder link_holder instructure_file_link_holder\"><a id=\"81279503\" class=\"inline_disabled preview_in_overlay\" title=\"Link\" href=\"https://canvas.colorado.edu/courses/123249/files/81280790?wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\" data-canvas-previe